Desmodium incanum

   [893.jpg]
    Authority   (J.F. Gmel.) Schinz & Thell.
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Rosidae:Fabales:Leguminosae
     Synonyms   Desmodium canum
   Common names kaimi clover
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 893

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A legume with fibrous to woody trailing and creeping
   stems reaching up to 30-60 cm in height. It has a deep, branched root
   system. Leaves trifoliate, flowers reddish or lavender and pods 2.5-4
   cm long with four to seven seeds. USES Used for pasture and withstands
   heavy grazing. KILLING T Fairly tolerant of frost. GROWING PERIOD
   Perennial summer-growing legume. Good growth in wet season, reduced in
   the dry season. Flowers in about 90 days in north Queensland and in
   51-81 days in Hawaii. COMMON NAMES Kaimi clover, Kaimi, Pega-pega,
   Creeping beggar bean, Creeping beggar weed. FURTHER INF Scientific
   synonyms: D. canum, D. supinum, D. sparsifolium, Hedysarum canum, H.
   racemosum, Aeschynomene spicata. Kaimi clover is native of the Americas
   from southern United States to Argentina. In the southern hemisphere
   Kaimi clover extend south as far as 27Â°S. It occurs from sea level to
   900 m in Hawaii, and up to 1700 m in Colombia, but it is generally most
   suited for elevations below 300 m. Dry matter production is about 5-6.5
   t/ha.

   Sources
